This is a fantastic question. Can any devs provide insight?

Great questions! So a little bit about bittensor miners, each of them is actually a state of the art language model. The bittensor api makes it easy to launch and develop models that are part of the bittensor network. When you are a part of the network, you can query other models for information and actively determine how other miners can be used to solve your particular languange problem
Currently, we are focused on the language modeling with plans to expand into other modalities such as images and time series data in the future.

You can imagine bittensor network as a ML marketplace where a client can potentially query a large number of foundation language models for information. This design is similar to large networks that currently used by all of the top players in AI (googles, facebook, etc...)
Tao is effectively the currency of the marketplace, where holding tao gives you more power in the marketplace 🙂
Hope that answers your questions @chronicmariopartyplayer_and keep the questions coming!

How is the team thinking about the total addressable market for the network? In the bull case (where benchmarks support the claims you guys made in the whitepaper), how big can the network's valuation really get?

Also, at what point would the network reach sufficient decentralization? The team has made comments about the IPFS nodes failing due to centralization. Is this the last step before the network reaches decentralization?

Without speculation, the bull case for Bittensor as a network is that we grow to control not just language, but image and other modalities centering us squarely as a foundational technology for AI in general. Your cleaning robot was built off of knowledge from Bittensor, your self driving car was build off of knowledge from Bittensor, your search engine understands your inputs, and your hedge fund of choice uses intelligence at some point mined on Bittensor. The market is, by some estimates 100 billion to 1 trillion over a ten year period.

So in our network, there are majorly 3 types of miner 
(1) a server that serves a ML model
(2) a validator that validates the servers
(3) a template miner that is both (1) and (2)

Then, it would be a validator's job to define which model is better. For instance, a validator can define its own NLP task / own dataset. Next, the validator would send request to the servers asking for a representation of a specific input. If the representation is useful for that validator's  own task, it would be revealed from the sparsely-gated-mixture-of-expert of  the validator. And the validator would set weight to the servers, ie giving them higher share of Tao.

So a "better" model would be defined as the model that can suit more of the use case of a validator that has more stake.

Definitions of intelligence almost always center around easy to understand benchmarks like the famous SuperGlue and GLue for language and ImageNet for visual inputs. The eventual value for Bittensor will come from showing that models trained on Bittensor are superior on these benchmarks, either through raw accuracy, being smaller and more compressed, or being able to train faster.

The Tao wars is the race toward and fight over governance of the largest superintelligence, represented by Bittensor $TAO holdings, which grants validation power over contributors of intelligence and service priority to consume and utilize the intelligence.
Secondary markets would accumulate $TAO, the way Convex and [Redacted] cartel is accumulating Curve tokens for the Curve wars.
The Tao wars are about intelligence liquidity, whereas the Curve wars are about currency liquidity. Presuming that the future will see growing significant adoption of AI to power large industries, certainly a view which many are supporting, intelligence liquidity could become much more well capitalized.

Bittensor is the only project I know of that offers an incentivized game-theoretic mathematical solution to decentralizing AI, namely a viable consensus-for-intelligence. This alone should already command a market premium, regardless of how long it takes to perfect the AI modeling utilizing this consensus.

My personal 20-year view on this space is underlined by the upward trends in AI tech, world connectivity, compute improvements, which will make distributed AI increasingly good and eventually superior to any single corporate effort. Decentralization is catalyzed and incentivized by consensus-for-intelligence, and alignment of world-scale compute on par with BTC and ETH v1 kick-starts a new web3 narrative on AI. Like I tend to say, we're 5-10 years before we'll see widespread recognition and adoption for this narrative, and early adopters may see outsized return for their astute foresight.

Of course, above is just my personal long-term motivation for my attention toward bittensor, without speaking of the short-term, mid-term, actual utility in e.g. providing generative language services modeled after OpenAI GPT3, and what the market valuation for that should be. I won't comment much on that, other than recommending to look at similar AI valuations, e.g. OpenAI has received $1B in funding, which is largely drained just in compute, without strong ROI guarantees. Personally, I don't think $100M for the future potential of Bittensor is overpriced. Not financial advice.

This is a great question. First, we have not yet got the chance to talk with Yoshio. 

I believe you’re right that the community is pretty anti crypto. This seems to be because the crypto ethos is anti authority and the AI industry is almost entirely academic.  

This is one of our selling points since we think there are many engineers out there looking for something which is less blue chip. We’re that option. Blue chip industries built of accolade and prestige always forget people along the way, we can be that alternative avenue.

As for go to market. We have to be honest here that as of yet we have not created something which is of very much interest. Without reaching SOTA on one task, doing it cheaper, or compressing into a smaller model, Bittensor is just a very cool science project. We haven’t reached those goals 2 month in. 

However where Bittensor will shows value will be with small to medium sized companies who are looking to push performance on their specific problems. Otter, Quill etc We could go to them now and help them coalesce those solutions or we could wait for bittensor to reach SOTA and have them come to us. Empirically, what basis is there for believing this architecture can achieve some comparative advantage over centralized equivalents -- be it in achieving SoTA results, higher training/inference efficiency, cost structure improvement etc.? From talking to folks at eleuther.ai their response tended towards a wholesale rejection of distributed models' feasibility due to the orders of magnitude higher latency introduced.  I've read the "Training Transformers Together" work that outlined ways to gain back what's lost in efficiency but I'm still struggling to gain intuition about how bittensor functions, as it seems radically different to me than the architectures I'm (loosely) familiar with.

Decentralized systems require more computational energy to maintain there is no doubt about it. Their advantages come from their ability to scale into compute otherwise untouched (stranded compute) and with digital currencies price that compute with efficiency a centralized body is unable to. (Markets efficiency, like Bitcoin)

As for latency, we understand that over-web communication introduces load but as the edge points scale our bottle neck is replaced with the raw computation burden of the models. I.e. inference on GPTJ is slower than the communication to it. 

Where Bittensor shines is I believe in the ability for us to restructure the way in which we are incentivizing the creation of intelligence itself, replacing the standard academic competition with markets. In other words the inefficiency of our current substrate creating Mintelligence is not the compute but meta to the machine learning systems themselves, at the level of the researcher/company/acedemic competition. Bittensor is a revolution on this front.
Bittensor is an Ai company of sorts but one which runs with a market backbone. Think of it that way.

There's another bit here, there seems to be some misunderstanding over the latency that eleuther seems to always be bringing up. Singular bittensor models aren't distributed over many computers. Each computer is running their own model and doing backpropagation on the same hardware. It's many models talking to many models

I think a better estimate is based on token inflation and price. In the same way that you can approximate Bitcoin hash power by looking at the price.

We are early right now and the ratio between mining costs and token price have diverged based on speculation. However as the market matures we hope that the cost of compute will begin to match the inflation rewards. 

Suppose the price were $50 USD and token inflation were still at 7600 tao per day then we could reasonably assume aggregated computing costs reaching 138,700,000 over a single year.
